"A bit thin with just hints of BBA character. A bit of heat and actually quite boozy. A good quad overall, but falls short as a BBA one. I expect some age to do some good for this brew."
""
"I'll say up front, I've grown to be quite a fan of Clown Shoes; they make some really good beer, and they are responsive and friendly on forums here. But, this offering falls a little short. In the taste, there are hints of brilliance—cherry, toffee, stonefruits, molasses, tobacco, smooth bourbon—but it is all a bit messy and harsh. Don't get me wrong, it's good, and for a lot of breweries, it would be the best in their portfolio; but relative to the high bar CS have set for themselves, it leaves a little to be desired. I may have to buy another bottle, because if another 18+ months smooth this out at all, it would be a giantkiller."
""
""
"Has a fruity, plum, bourbon spice nose. Pours Chestnut with a slight haze under an off-white foam cap. It has a super creamy palate with bourbon, toffee, vanilla and spice. A light initial sweetness dries on the finish. There is some alcohol heat that grows on its way to your stomach. The carbonation is very soft and airy and gives the beer an impression of less body than it actually has. As it warms the bourbon becomes more apparent."
""
"I love the subtle bourbon barrel notes. Not overpowering, JUST right. The quad itself is a little thin. Very little head, no lacing, somewhat watery mouth feel, a little too sour for the style. Overall I think the beer is still successful, but it's all in the taste. Pricy, but worth it if subtle bourbon barrel notes in a quad sound like your thing..."
